<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-307-111  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 307 111.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Jan 16 1989 n296 p81(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Georgia embarks on project to automate public schools; goal:create sophisticated information system by 1994.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pang, Albert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Georgia embarks on an ambitious project to automate its publicschool system with the Statewide Information System (SIS) project.andO;SIS will radically reform the day-to-day operations of the state's1,800 elementary and secondary schools, along with 30 othertechnical and vocational schools.andP;  The project, scheduled forcompletion in 1994, was designed to replace the now-in-placeinformation system with one that is equipped with specializedapplications that run on minicomputers, local area networks andstand-alone microcomputers.andP;  SIS will have access to scores ofdata, ranging from grade results to attendance records, on morethan 1.3 million students in the state.andP;  The Task Force on theEducation Information Network has already approved a total of 10pilot programs and allocated about $20 million worth of contractsto hardware and software vendors, VARs and consultants.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     GeorgiaElementary SchoolsSecondary SchoolsProduct DevelopmentInformation SystemsLocal Area NetworksVocational EducationMinicomputersMicrocomputers.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Statewide information system. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>